Does this mean that in the scenario you described, a new developer menu activity would not be started?

Yes, that's right.
If you are okay with not supporting shake to dismiss, using the FLAG_ACTIVITY_SINGLE_TOP would probably give you a complete solution.
If you do want to support shake to dismiss, it is a bit more complex.  I think you could accomplish it though with something like the logic below.  It's not my favorite idea, because it still involves maintaining a static state, but I'm not sure of a different solution - it's definitely a tricky problem.
class DevMenuManager implements ShakeDetector.Listener {
    private boolean visible;

    private static DevMenuManager sInstance = new DevMenuManager();

    public static sharedInstance() {
         return sInstance;
    }

    public start() {
         // Subscribe to shake events
    }

    public void onShakeDetected() {
         if(visible) {
            Amplify.Hub.publish("HideDeveloperMenu");  // this syntax is probably wrong, but the idea is to broadcast a message on Hub.  Then, you would listen for this message in `DeveloperMenuActivity`, and call finish when you receive the message.
visible = false;
         } else {
            Intent mainIntent = new Intent(context, DeveloperMenuActivity.class);
            mainIntent.setAction(Intent.ACTION_MAIN);
            mainIntent.setFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);
            context.startActivity(mainIntent);
            visible = true;
       }
   }
}

In Amplify.configure():
DevMenuManager.sharedInstance().start()

In DeveloperMenuActivity.onCreate():
Amplify.Hub.subscribe("HideDeveloperMenu", event -> {
      finish();
});

