timeline.bodyText:
Just an idea -- feel free to ignore --
Instead of using the boolean, you could encode this behavior in your callback:
final class ShakeDetector {
    private final ShakeDetector.Listener listener;

    ShakeDetector(ShakeDetector.Listener listener) {
        this.listener = listener;
    }

    // Change this
    @FunctionalInterface
    interface Listener {
        void onShakeDetected(ShakeDetector source);
    }
}
Then you'll have an instance to call stopDetecting() on, in your lambda:
ShakeDetector detector = new ShakeDetector(context, it -> {
    context.startActivity(mainIntent);
    it.stopDetecting();
});
Without changing the listener, you could already do:
final AtomicReference<ShakeDetector.Listener> listener = new AtomicReference<>();
ShakeDetector detector = new ShakeDetector(context, () -> {
    context.startActivity(mainIntent);
    listener.get().stopDetecting();
});
^ This would give you a final reference inside of your lambda. The AtomicReference thing is sort of a kludge that I try to avoid if I can, though.

